public class java_50146_SocketServer_A07 {  // Note: Server-side is just a single Socket at any given time, client side can be multiple concurrently connecting clients as well - in fact it's usually many connected to different servers of similar purpose. Both are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {  // The method starts from 'main'. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate. Both are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
        System.out.println("Starting AuthServer...");   // The method starts from 'main'. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
        
        int port = 9876;  // The method starts from 'main'. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
        boolean running = true;   // Keep our program "running" till we shut it down. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
        
        ServerSocket listener = new ServerSocket(port);  // The method starts from 'main'. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
        
        while (running) {  // Our program will keep running until we shut it down. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
            try {   // Attempt to accept a connection from one of our clients. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                Socket socket = listener.accept();  // Accept a new connection from our clients (our ServerSocket). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                System.out.println("Accepted connection from: " + socket.getRemoteSocketAddress());  // Notify us about which client accepted our new connections (our ServerSocket). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // Now you can read from this socket to get user input if it's a text-based protocol. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // For example: BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader (socket.getInputStream()));  Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // String data = reader.readLine();   Here you can read input from user (client). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // Now respond to this data. You can use whatever responses you want based upon your application's needs (e.g., OK/FAIL, AUTH_SUCCESS or USERNAME+PASSWORD) Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // For example: PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(socket.getOutputStream()); Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // Your response should be something along these lines: writer.println("AUTH_SUCCESS"); Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                // Remember to close your streams/connections once you're done with them. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
                socket.close();  // Close this connection once done with it (our new connections). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                
            } catch(IOException e) {  // If an error occurs whilst accepting a connection (our ServerSocket). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                e.printStackTrace();  // Print out what exception was caught (our IOException). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
                running = false;  // Stop our program if an error occurs. This will prevent us from accepting new connections (our ServerSocket). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate - all are used here only for the sake demonstrating auth mechanism on server end and nothing more than that
            }  // End of try/catch block. All exceptions (our IOException) will be caught by our catch clause in this while loop which is what allows us to keep accepting connections even if something goes wrong with them - done via running = false; line above the catching error scenario. Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate – all are used here only for demonstration of A07_AuthFailure and nothing more than that
        } // End while loop (our program will keep running till we shut it down). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate – all are used here only for demonstration of A07_AuthFailure and nothing more than that
        
        listener.close(); // Close the listening socket when we're done with it (our ServerSocket). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate – all are used here only for demonstration of A07_AuthFailure and nothing more than that
    } // End main method. All exceptions will be caught by our catch block - done via running = false; line above the catching error scenario (our IOException). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate – all are used here only for demonstration of A07_AuthFailure and nothing more than that
} // End class AuthServer. All exceptions will be caught by our catch block - done via running = false; line above the catching error scenario (our IOException). Including ServerSocket which is needed in both client & server side code, but not using frameworks like Spring or Hibernate – all are used here only for demonstration of A07_AuthFailure and nothing more than that